   <titles>
      <title>Partial Sums of a Series: Examples</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Partial sums of a constant series</strong>   The first five partial sums of the constant series with summands equal to <math>
                     <latex>3</latex>
                  </math> are</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
\begin{array}{rcl}
s_0 &amp; = &amp; 3 \\
s_1 &amp; = &amp; 3 + 3 = 6 \\
s_2 &amp; = &amp; 3 + 3 + 3 = 9 \\
s_3 &amp; = &amp; 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 12 \\
s_4 &amp; = &amp; 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 15 \\
s_n &amp; = &amp; (n+1)\cdot 3
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Partial sums of the harmonic series</strong>   The first five partial sums of the harmonic series are</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
\begin{array}{rcl}
s_1 &amp; = &amp; 1 \\
s_2 &amp; = &amp; 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} = \dfrac{3}{2} \\
s_3 &amp; = &amp; 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} = \dfrac{11}{6} \\
s_4 &amp; = &amp; 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \dfrac{1}{4} = \dfrac{25}{12} \\
s_5 &amp; = &amp; 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{3} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \dfrac{1}{5} = \dfrac{137}{60}
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <strong>Partial sums of a geometric series</strong>   The first five partial sums of the geometric series associated to <math>
                     <latex>r\neq 1/2</latex>
                  </math> are</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
\begin{array}{rcl}
s_0 &amp; = &amp; 1 \\
s_1 &amp; = &amp; 1+ \dfrac{1}{2} = \dfrac{3}{2} \\
s_2 &amp; = &amp; 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{4} = \dfrac{7}{4} \\
s_3 &amp; = &amp; 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \dfrac{1}{8} = \dfrac{15}{8} \\
s_4 &amp; = &amp; 1 + \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{1}{4} + \dfrac{1}{8} + \dfrac{1}{16} =  \dfrac{31}{16}
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>For a geometric series with <math>
                     <latex>r\neq 1</latex>
                  </math>, we are lucky: it is possible to write out the <math>
                     <latex>n</latex>
                  </math>-th partial sum using a simple formula:
				</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>geometric</term>
                  <term>series</term>
                  <term>partial sum</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The <math>
                              <latex>n</latex>
                           </math>-th partial sum of the geometric series is</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>s_n = \sum_{k=0}^{n} r^k = \dfrac{1-r^{k+1}}{1-r}</latex>
                     </math.display>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>s_n</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>1 + r+ r^2 + r^3 + \cdots + r^n</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex/>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>(1 + r+ r^2 + r^3 + \cdots + r^n)\cdot \dfrac{1-r}{1-r}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex/>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>=</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\dfrac{1-r^{n+1}}{1-r}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
         </block.body>
      </block>
